# CaptionDB Performance Engineering Contract

## Purpose

This contract defines the mandatory performance engineering standards for CaptionDB.

Performance is a first-class engineering concern.

The objective is to maximize:

- Throughput
- Responsiveness
- Resource efficiency
- Scalability
- Cost efficiency

while maintaining correctness.

---

# Performance Philosophy

Never optimize blindly.

Measure first.

Profile second.

Optimize third.

Verify improvements.

Every optimization must have measurable benefits.

---

# Engineering Goals

Optimize for:

- Lower latency
- Lower memory usage
- Lower CPU utilization
- Lower GPU idle time
- Lower API token usage
- Lower network overhead
- Lower Docker image size
- Faster startup
- Faster processing
- Better scalability

---

# Performance Principles

Always:

Avoid unnecessary work.

Avoid repeated work.

Avoid unnecessary allocations.

Avoid unnecessary API requests.

Avoid unnecessary disk operations.

Avoid unnecessary serialization.

---

# Profiling

Profile before optimization.

Use profiling tools.

Measure:

CPU

Memory

Disk I/O

Network

Latency

GPU utilization (where applicable)

Never guess performance bottlenecks.

---

# Caching Philosophy

Cache expensive operations only.

Examples:

Scene Detection

OCR Results

Video Metadata

Embeddings

Prompt Templates

Configuration

Vision Analysis

Never cache mutable business state.

---

# Cache Rules

Every cache should define:

TTL

Eviction policy

Maximum size

Cache key strategy

Invalidation strategy

Configuration driven.

---

# Memory Management

Avoid unnecessary copies.

Release large objects quickly.

Stream large files when possible.

Reuse allocated resources.

Avoid loading entire videos into memory unless required.

---

# Video Processing

Process videos incrementally.

Avoid reading the same video multiple times.

Reuse extracted metadata.

Avoid duplicate frame extraction.

---

# Frame Sampling

Frame extraction must be efficient.

Avoid extracting frames that will never be used.

Support configurable sampling strategies.

Avoid redundant processing.

---

# OCR Optimization

OCR should run only when enabled.

Avoid OCR on duplicate frames.

Cache OCR results.

Skip empty scenes when appropriate.

---

# Fireworks Optimization

Reduce:

API calls

Prompt size

Image count

Token usage

Latency

Reuse context whenever possible.

Prefer batch operations where supported.

---

# Prompt Optimization

Prompt templates should be concise.

Avoid unnecessary instructions.

Avoid duplicated context.

Support reusable prompt fragments.

Version prompts.

---

# Parallel Processing

Parallelize only independent work.

Examples:

Independent scenes

OCR

Vision analysis

Caption generation

Avoid race conditions.

Avoid excessive thread creation.

---

# Concurrency

Concurrency should be configurable.

Do not hardcode worker counts.

Respect system resources.

Avoid oversubscription.

---

# Async Programming

Use asynchronous operations for:

Network requests

I/O

External services

Avoid async for CPU-bound work.

---

# Worker Management

Background workers should:

Reuse resources

Limit concurrency

Handle graceful shutdown

Report metrics

Avoid resource leaks.

---

# Resource Reuse

Reuse:

HTTP Clients

Fireworks Clients

OCR Engines

Configuration

Prompt Templates

Avoid recreating expensive objects.

---

# Lazy Loading

Load heavy resources only when needed.

Examples:

Models

OCR

Large configuration

Embeddings

Avoid unnecessary startup costs.

---

# Startup Performance

Application startup should:

Load configuration

Validate environment

Initialize required services

Delay optional initialization.

Target fast startup.

---

# Database Performance

When persistence is introduced:

Avoid N+1 queries.

Use pagination.

Index frequently queried fields.

Avoid unnecessary joins.

Use connection pooling.

---

# API Performance

Minimize payload size.

Compress responses when appropriate.

Avoid unnecessary serialization.

Return only required fields.

---

# Frontend Performance

Support:

Lazy loading

Code splitting

Memoization

Efficient rendering

Avoid unnecessary re-renders.

---

# Docker Performance

Optimize:

Layer caching

Image size

Dependency installation

Startup

Container memory usage

Use multi-stage builds.

---

# Build Performance

Leverage Docker cache.

Pin dependency versions.

Avoid rebuilding unchanged layers.

Separate dependencies from application code.

---

# Logging Performance

Avoid excessive logging.

Use DEBUG only when necessary.

Do not log inside tight loops unless required.

---

# Metrics

Collect:

Processing time

Request latency

Fireworks latency

OCR latency

Scene detection duration

Frame extraction duration

Export duration

CPU

Memory

Cache hit ratio

Token usage

Retries

Queue length

---

# Benchmarking

Benchmark every major optimization.

Compare:

Before

After

Record measurable improvements.

Never claim improvements without evidence.

---

# Scalability

Design for:

More videos

Longer videos

Multiple users

Future GPU scaling

Future distributed workers

Avoid architecture that limits growth.

---

# Feature Flags

Performance features should be configurable.

Examples:

Caching

Parallelism

OCR

Memory

Judge

Batch processing

Experimental optimizations

---

# Resource Limits

Support configurable limits.

Examples:

Maximum upload size

Maximum concurrent videos

Maximum workers

Maximum retries

Maximum memory usage

Maximum processing duration

---

# Observability

Every performance-critical service should expose:

Execution time

Average latency

Failure rate

Retry count

Memory usage

CPU usage

Throughput

These metrics should support future monitoring.

---

# Optimization Workflow

Before implementing optimization:

Measure

↓

Identify bottleneck

↓

Design improvement

↓

Implement

↓

Benchmark

↓

Validate

↓

Document

Never optimize blindly.

---

# Testing

Performance-sensitive code should include:

Benchmark tests

Stress tests

Load tests

Memory tests

Regression tests

Performance improvements must not reduce correctness.

---

# Documentation

Document:

Performance assumptions

Caching strategy

Parallelism strategy

Resource limits

Optimization decisions

Benchmark results

---

# Performance Review Checklist

Before completing implementation verify:

✓ No unnecessary work

✓ Expensive operations cached

✓ Resources reused

✓ Async used correctly

✓ Parallelism justified

✓ Memory optimized

✓ Startup optimized

✓ Docker optimized

✓ Metrics collected

✓ Benchmarks performed

✓ Scalability considered

✓ Documentation updated

✓ Tests added

If any item fails, revise implementation before completion.

---

End of Performance Engineering Contract.
